## **Oval Diamond: The 2026 Trend Leader**

**The oval is the fastest-growing diamond shape in 2026, offering 10–15% more apparent surface area than a round of equal carat weight at 20–30% lower price.**

![Minimal luxury infographic of an oval diamond showing its larger appearance, lower price compared to round, and highlighting the bow-tie effect with a clean editorial design.](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/oval-diamond-2026-trend-leader-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Oval Unique?**

The oval cut is essentially an elongated round brilliant — featuring the same 57–58 facet arrangement as a round but stretched into an elliptical outline. This elongation creates two distinct advantages: the stone appears larger than its carat weight suggests, and the elongated shape visually lengthens the finger when oriented north-south.

The oval's brilliance is exceptional — it scatters light in nearly the same pattern as a round brilliant, making it one of the most forgiving fancy shapes for inclusions and color. A G-VS2 oval looks nearly identical to a D-VS1 oval in a mounted ring at arm's length.

### **The Bow-Tie Effect: The Oval's Critical Risk**

Some oval cut diamonds may have something called the "bow-tie effect," which is a darkened area across its middle. The amount of darkness varies, so look for an oval cut diamond with a minimal bow-tie to maximize light performance and your investment.

The bow-tie is a dark shadow resembling a bow tie that appears across the widest point of some oval diamonds. It is caused by the elongated facet pattern failing to redirect light from certain viewing angles.

Every oval has some degree of bow-tie — the question is severity. Minor bow-ties are acceptable and even add character. Severe bow-ties visually bisect the stone and destroy its beauty.

**The bow-tie audit rule:** Never purchase an oval diamond without watching a 360° HD video in multiple lighting conditions. The **[Blue Nile review](https://diamondcritics.com/blue-nile-review/)** covers their imaging quality — essential for evaluating oval bow-tie severity before purchase.

