t to find a stone where the bow-tie is faint and blends smoothly into the sparkle, rather than appearing as a stark black shadow.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Finger lengthening effect</strong></td><td>Significant (north-south setting)</td><td><strong>9/10. The Elegant Silhouette.</strong> Unlike the blunt width of a round or cushion, the elongated oval draws the eye down the hand, creating a highly flattering, slimming effect on the wearer's finger.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>Prong solitaire, east-west bezel</td><td><strong>8/10. Versatile Protection.</strong> A 4-prong solitaire maximizes light, but a bezel setting (especially oriented east-west) offers ultimate protection for the vulnerable tips while delivering a hyper-modern editorial aesthetic.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.30–1.50</td><td><strong>10/10. The Proportion Spectrum.</strong> A 1.30 creates a "chubby" oval close to a round, while a 1.50 delivers a sleek, stretched profile. 1.40 is the traditional gold standard for the perfect balance of width and length.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Oval Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The oval is the optimal shape for buyers who want maximum apparent size for their budget, a finger-lengthening effect, and brilliance comparable to a round — at 20–30% lower price. It suits slender hands particularly well. The east-west setting trend — rotating the oval 90 degrees — has made oval diamonds popular with modern, fashion-forward buyers.

