## **Cushion Cut Diamond: The Vintage-Modern Hybrid**

**The cushion cut combines a square or rectangular outline with rounded corners and a brilliant facet pattern — producing a vintage aesthetic with modern light performance.**

![Minimal luxury infographic of a cushion cut diamond comparing chunky and crushed ice styles, highlighting its vintage aesthetic, modern sparkle, and value compared to round diamonds.](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/cushion-diamond-vintage-modern-hybrid-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Cushion Unique?**

The cushion cut has roots in the "old mine cut" diamonds of the 18th and 19th centuries — which had large, open culets, high crowns, and chunky facets. Modern cushion cuts retain the rounded-corner square outline but apply contemporary brilliant-cut faceting for dramatically improved light performance.

Two distinct cushion varieties exist in the market:

**Standard Cushion (Chunky)**: Larger facets that produce broad, bold flashes of light — closer to the old mine cut aesthetic. More fire and color dispersion. Often appears more "antique" or romantic.

**Modified Cushion (Crushed Ice):** Smaller, more numerous facets producing rapid scintillation similar to a round brilliant. The pattern resembles crushed ice or a sparkling mosaic. More modern appearance, slightly more similar to a round in optical behavior.

The "crushed ice" pattern has the added advantage of better masking inclusions — making modified cushions slightly more forgiving of lower clarity grades.

Cushion cuts retain color more than other shapes, so look for an H color or better when the diamond is set in platinum, white gold, or silver. This color retention is important — a cushion cut in I or J color will appear noticeably warmer than a round of the same color grade, especially in white metal settings.

### **Cushion Diamond: The Data Profile**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Cushion Diamond Data</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Varieties</strong></td><td>Standard (chunky) vs. Modified (crushed ice)</td><td><strong>9/10. The Dual Personality.</strong> "Chunky" standard cuts offer antique-style broad flashes of light, while "crushed ice" modified cushions deliver chaotic, high-frequency, glittering sparkle. You must audit videos to ensure you get the specific flavor you want.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Price vs. round</strong></td><td>20–30% less</td><td><strong>9/10. The Budget Softener.</strong> Because the cushion shape naturally follows the raw diamond crystal, cutters waste far less rough material. They pass this massive 20-30% discount directly to the buyer.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Clarity requirement</strong></td><td>VS2–SI1 acceptable (modified cushion more forgiving)</td><td><strong>10/10. The Ultimate Concealer.</strong> The "crushed ice" modified cushions are practically bulletproof when it comes to hiding SI1 inclusions. The dense, busy faceting acts as a natural camouflage.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Color sensitivity</strong></td><td>High — H or better in white gold/platinum</td><td><strong>6/10. The Color Trap.</strong> Cushions hold onto warmth more than almost any other brilliant cut. If you want an icy look in white metal, do not drop below an H. However, this same trait makes them spectacular for maximizing a J-color stone in a yellow gold setting.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Bow-tie effect</strong></td><td>Rare — rectangular cushions occasionally</td><td><strong>9/10. Safe from Shadows.</strong> Unlike ovals and pears, square cushions are largely immune to the dreaded dark bow-tie across the center, giving you consistent edge-to-edge light return.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Finger effect</strong></td><td>Compact — suits wider hands</td><td><strong>7/10. The Substantial Look.</strong> Rather than lengthening the finger, the soft, rounded square commands a broad, solid footprint. It is incredibly flattering on wider fingers where slender shapes might look lost.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>Halo, pavé, bezel</td><td><strong>10/10. The Halo Champion.</strong> No shape looks better in a halo than a cushion cut. The softly rounded corners blend seamlessly into a diamond perimeter, often making a 1-carat center stone look like a 2-carat piece.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.00–1.05 (square) or 1.10–1.20 (rectangular)</td><td><strong>8/10. The Custom Fit.</strong> A 1.00 ratio gives you the classic, symmetrical "pillow" square, while pushing toward 1.15 offers an elongated rectangle that mimics a radiant cut with softer edges.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Depth guidance</strong></td><td>Under 70% depth and table</td><td><strong>8/10. The Spread Rule.</strong> Cushions are notoriously deep, meaning they often hide dead weight below the girdle. Keeping the depth and table percentages under 70% ensures you aren't paying for invisible carats, maximizing the face-up size.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Cushion Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The cushion is ideal for buyers who love a romantic, vintage aesthetic with modern brilliance. The halo setting is the most popular cushion pairing — adding a ring of surrounding diamonds that amplifies the apparent size and scintillation. A one-carat cushion cut costs around $2,500 based on quality recommendations — significantly less than a comparable round brilliant.

