## **Princess Cut Diamond: The Square Brilliant**

**The princess cut is a square or slightly rectangular brilliant cut — the second most popular shape historically, now declining as oval and cushion gain market share.**

![Princess cut diamond infographic showing square shape brilliance and corner chipping risk in a luxury editorial layout](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/princess-cut-diamond-square-brilliant-editorial-infographic-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Princess Unique?**

The princess cut was developed in the 1960s and refined through the 1980s and 1990s. It features a square outline with pointed corners and approximately 76 facets in a modified brilliant pattern. The result is higher light return than most fancy shapes — second only to the round brilliant in objective brilliance measurements.

The princess cut's appeal is its clean, modern geometry — a square outline that reads as contemporary and architectural while delivering brilliant-cut light performance. It is popular in channel and pavé settings where its straight edges align with the surrounding band.

#### **The structural warning**

The princess cut's four sharp corners are its greatest vulnerability. Corner inclusions — feathers, crystals, or knots positioned at the tips of the stone — are both a visual concern and a structural risk.

Corner inclusions weaken the structural integrity at the most vulnerable points of the stone, where prong pressure during setting can cause chipping. V-prong settings are mandatory for princess cuts — they cover and protect the corners while minimizing metal visibility.

### **Princess Diamond: The Data Profile**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Princess Diamond Data</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Facet count</strong></td><td>~76</td><td><strong>9/10. The Scintillation Powerhouse.</strong> With up to 76 facets, the Princess cut is engineered for high-frequency sparkle. This dense facet pattern makes it a top-tier choice for hiding small inclusions.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Brilliance vs. round</strong></td><td>High — second among shapes</td><td><strong>10/10. The Sparkle Runner-Up.</strong> It is widely considered the most brilliant of all square/rectangular cuts. If you want "Round-level" fire in a modern, angular silhouette, this is the only real contender.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Price vs. round</strong></td><td>20–30% less</td><td><strong>9/10. Maximum Rough Efficiency.</strong> Because the pyramid shape of a Princess cut mimics the natural octahedral shape of a rough diamond, cutters keep nearly 80% of the stone. You get more carats for a significantly lower price.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Clarity requirement</strong></td><td>VS1–VS2; reject corner inclusions</td><td><strong>5/10. The Structural Red Flag.</strong> While the center is forgiving, inclusions near the corners are a deal-breaker. A "feather" or "crystal" in the corner can cause the stone to crack under the pressure of a setting tool.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Color sensitivity</strong></td><td>Moderate-High</td><td><strong>6/10. The Corner Tint.</strong> Body color tends to pool in the four sharp corners. If you’re sensitive to warmth, stay at G-color or higher to ensure the points don't look yellow against a white gold setting.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Structural risk</strong></td><td>Corner chipping risk</td><td><strong>4/10. Handle with Care.</strong> Those sharp 90-degree points are vulnerable. One accidental smack against a granite countertop can chip a corner. This is a shape that demands protective housing.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>V-prong solitaire, channel pavé</td><td><strong>10/10. The V-Prong Mandate.</strong> Standard prongs leave the corners exposed. V-prongs wrap around the points, acting as a "roll cage" for the diamond’s most fragile areas.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.00–1.05 (square)</td><td><strong>10/10. Symmetrical Modernism.</strong> Anything over 1.05 looks like an "accidental" rectangle. To capture the true Princess aesthetic, you want a perfect 1.00 ratio for that crisp, balanced look.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Princess Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The princess cut suits buyers who want a square, modern aesthetic with brilliant-cut light performance — at 20–30% below round pricing. It is particularly suited to straight-line contemporary settings and Art Deco inspired designs.

The declining popularity of princess cuts in 2026 means some buyers find it slightly dated — the cushion cut has taken much of the princess cut's market share among square-preferring buyers.

