## **Pear Diamond: The Elongated Teardrop**

**The pear cut combines the round brilliant's optical performance with a pointed tip and elongated silhouette — appearing significantly larger than its carat weight suggests.**

![Pear shaped diamond infographic showing elongated brilliance with bow tie effect and tip chipping risk in luxury editorial style](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/pear-diamond-elongated-teardrop-editorial-infographic-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Pear Unique?**

The pear cut (also called teardrop) features a rounded base narrowing to a single point. It is a modified brilliant cut with 58 facets, inheriting most of the round brilliant's light performance while adding a distinctive silhouette.

Like the oval, the pear's elongated shape creates a finger-lengthening effect and apparent size advantage — a 1ct pear appears larger than a 1ct round when measured across the diagonal.

The pear's asymmetric shape creates a directional ring design — the pointed tip is always oriented toward the fingernail in traditional settings (north orientation). East-west pear settings — rotating the stone 90 degrees — have become a popular modern alternative.

#### **The bow-tie and tip risks**

Like the oval, pear diamonds can develop a bow-tie effect across the widest section. Additionally, the pointed tip is a structural vulnerability — inclusions at or near the tip weaken the stone at its most fragile point.

Tip inclusions also concentrate visual attention at the most visible part of the stone. Always verify tip clarity on the GIA plot and video.

### **Pear Diamond: The Data Profile**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Pear Diamond Data</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Facet count</strong></td><td>58</td><td><strong>10/10. Standard Brilliance.</strong> Utilizing the same 58-facet structure as a round brilliant, the pear delivers that high-end fire and scintillation that hides inclusions in the "belly" of the stone.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Apparent size vs. round</strong></td><td>10–15% larger surface area</td><td><strong>10/10. The Visual Giant.</strong> Because of its elongated shape, a 1-carat pear will almost always look significantly larger than a 1-carat round. It’s the ultimate way to "cheat" your way into a bigger-looking ring.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Price vs. round</strong></td><td>25–35% less</td><td><strong>9/10. High Efficiency.</strong> Cutters can follow the organic "teardrop" shape of many rough stones, leading to less waste and a massive price discount for the consumer.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Clarity requirement</strong></td><td>VS1–VS2; reject tip inclusions</td><td><strong>5/10. The Tip Trap.</strong> While the wide end is forgiving, the point acts like a magnet for dark inclusions. If a crystal is trapped in the point, it is highly visible and can even lead to structural cracking.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Bow-tie effect</strong></td><td>Present — severity varies</td><td><strong>6/10. The Necessary Audit.</strong> Like ovals, all pears have a bow-tie. You aren't looking for "none"—you're looking for one that is subtle and doesn't "kill" the light return in the center.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Structural risk</strong></td><td>Tip chipping without V-prong</td><td><strong>4/10. Handle with Caution.</strong> The point of a pear is its most vulnerable feature. Without a V-prong "roll cage," a single accidental hit against a hard surface can chip the point instantly.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Finger effect</strong></td><td>Strong lengthening effect</td><td><strong>10/10. The Sculptor.</strong> By drawing the eye along the length of the stone, the pear cut creates a slimming, elegant silhouette that makes any finger look longer and more graceful.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>V-prong at tip, east-west bezel</td><td><strong>9/10. Trend vs. Function.</strong> Traditionalists love the V-prong for protection, but the 2026 trend is the "East-West" bezel, which mounts the stone horizontally for a bold, modern editorial look.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.45–1.75</td><td><strong>8/10. Taste-Dependent.</strong> A 1.45 ratio creates a "chubby" pear, while 1.75 is sleek and needle-like. 1.55 to 1.60 is the sweet spot for the classic "Golden Teardrop" proportions.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Pear Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The pear is for buyers seeking maximum apparent size, a romantic asymmetric silhouette, and brilliant-cut light performance at 25–35% below round prices. It is particularly popular for pendant necklaces and vintage-inspired settings. The V-prong at the tip is non-negotiable — protecting the pointed tip from chipping during wear.

