## **Marquise Diamond: Maximum Perceived Size**

**The marquise cut is the most elongated standard diamond shape — producing the greatest apparent size per carat of any shape and an unmatched finger-lengthening effect.**

![Marquise cut diamond infographic showing elongated shape with dual tip vulnerability and bow-tie effect in luxury editorial style on white background](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/marquise-diamond-maximum-perceived-size-editorial-infographic-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Marquise Unique?**

The marquise (also called navette, from the French for "little boat") features two pointed tips connected by curved sides in an elongated football shape. Its facet pattern is a modified brilliant cut with 56–58 facets. The marquise's extreme elongation maximizes surface area — a 1ct marquise oriented north-south appears dramatically larger than a 1ct round from the viewer's perspective.

The shape has roots in 18th century France — legend attributes its creation to Louis XV, who reportedly commissioned a diamond cut to mimic the shape of the Marquise de Pompadour's lips. Whether true or not, the marquise has maintained a reputation for drama and romance throughout its history.

#### **The marquise carries two structural vulnerabilities**

Both pointed tips require V-prong protection, and tip inclusions on either point create both visual and structural concerns.

Additionally, marquise diamonds have one of the strongest bow-tie effect risks of any elongated shape — the geometry of the narrow, pointed ends creates dark zones at the waist that can be significant in poorly cut stones.

### **Marquise Diamond: The Data Profile**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Marquise Diamond Data</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Facet count</strong></td><td>56–58</td><td><strong>10/10. Standard Brilliance.</strong> Leveraging the same optical physics as the round brilliant, the marquise delivers high scintillation that effectively hides minor inclusions in the center.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Apparent size vs. round</strong></td><td>15–20% larger surface area</td><td><strong>10/10. The Size Champion.</strong> This shape provides the largest "face-up" area of any diamond cut. It is the ultimate visual hack for making a modest budget look like a massive investment.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Price vs. round</strong></td><td>25–35% less</td><td><strong>9/10. The Efficiency Winner.</strong> Because it follows the elongated grain of rough crystals, cutters keep more weight, passing the 25–35% savings directly to you.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Clarity requirement</strong></td><td>VS1–VS2; reject tip inclusions</td><td><strong>6/10. The Double Tip Trap.</strong> While the center masks flaws well, the two points act as magnets for inclusions. Dark crystals at the tips are a deal-breaker for both aesthetics and durability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Bow-tie effect</strong></td><td>High risk — always verify on video</td><td><strong>5/10. The Dark Shadow.</strong> Due to its extreme length-to-width ratio, the marquise is highly prone to a dark "bow-tie" across the middle. A rigorous 360-degree video audit is mandatory.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Structural risk</strong></td><td>Both tips require V-prong protection</td><td><strong>4/10. Brittle Points.</strong> Having two sharp points doubles the risk of chipping. These ends are thin and vulnerable; they must be shielded by V-prongs or a bezel to survive daily wear.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Finger effect</strong></td><td>Maximum lengthening</td><td><strong>10/10. The Hand Sculptor.</strong> No other shape slims or lengthens the finger as effectively. It is the most flattering choice for shorter fingers or those seeking a statuesque look.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>V-prong solitaire, east-west modern</td><td><strong>9/10. The Safety Protocol.</strong> Six-prong settings with V-caps at the ends are the gold standard. For a 2026 editorial look, a horizontal "East-West" mount offers a fresh, modern vibe.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.75–2.25</td><td><strong>10/10. The Proportion Rule.</strong> A 2.00 ratio is the "Golden Standard" for the classic marquise. Anything under 1.75 looks "squat," and anything over 2.25 appears too needle-like for most settings.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Marquise Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The marquise is for buyers who want the maximum "big ring" appearance for their budget and a dramatic, elongated look. It is the most flattering shape for shorter or wider fingers — the extreme elongation visually extends the finger more than any other shape.

At 25–35% below round pricing with 15–20% more perceived surface area, the marquise delivers the best apparent-size-per-dollar ratio in the diamond market.

