## **Radiant Cut Diamond: The Step-Brilliant Hybrid**

**The radiant cut is the only shape that combines step-cut geometry (rectangular outline) with brilliant-cut faceting (triangular/kite facets) — delivering the emerald cut's look with significantly more brilliance.**

![Radiant cut diamond infographic showing hybrid step-brilliant structure with crushed ice sparkle and beveled corners in luxury editorial style on white background](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/radiant-cut-diamond-step-brilliant-hybrid-editorial-infographic-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Radiant Unique?**

The radiant cut was created in 1977 by Henry Grossbard as a direct response to the emerald cut's inclusion sensitivity problem. By applying brilliant-cut faceting to a rectangular outline, Grossbard created a shape that could achieve the long, sleek proportions of the emerald cut while using brilliant-cut light scattering to mask inclusions more effectively.

The result is a versatile shape that appeals to buyers who love the rectangular or square outline but want more fire and scintillation than the emerald cut provides. The radiant is also available in both square (L/W ratio close to 1.00) and elongated rectangular forms.

The radiant's "crushed ice" appearance — when its numerous small facets catch light — is visually similar to the modified cushion cut. Many buyers choosing between cushion and radiant are making a corner decision: the cushion has rounded corners, the radiant has cropped (beveled) corners.

### **Radiant Diamond: The Data Profile**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Radiant Diamond Data</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Created</strong></td><td>1977 by Henry Grossbard</td><td><strong>10/10. The Original Hybrid.</strong> This was the first cut to successfully blend the sophisticated emerald silhouette with the fire of a round brilliant, changing the fancy-cut market forever.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Facet pattern</strong></td><td>Brilliant faceting in rectangular outline</td><td><strong>10/10. The "Crushed Ice" King.</strong> With up to 70 facets, the radiant creates a high-frequency sparkle that is far more energetic and forgiving than the broad flashes of a step-cut.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Price vs. round</strong></td><td>25–35% less</td><td><strong>9/10. The Value Play.</strong> Because the cut follows the natural rough crystal shape, waste is minimized. You can often secure a much larger stone for the same price as a modest round.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Clarity requirement</strong></td><td>VS2–SI1 acceptable</td><td><strong>10/10. The Ultimate Hider.</strong> The chaotic brilliance of a radiant is incredible at masking inclusions. An eye-clean SI1 is the "pro-move" here, saving you thousands without a visual trade-off.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Color sensitivity</strong></td><td>Moderate — H or better</td><td><strong>7/10. Depth Traps Color.</strong> Because radiants are deep, they tend to concentrate body color. If you want an icy look in white gold, stay at G or H; otherwise, warmth will be visible.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Bow-tie effect</strong></td><td>Possible in elongated radiants</td><td><strong>8/10. Minimal Risk.</strong> While present in some elongated stones, the brilliant faceting usually breaks up the shadow better than in ovals. A 360-degree video audit is still recommended.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Finger effect</strong></td><td>Moderate lengthening</td><td><strong>8/10. Versatile Silhouette.</strong> An elongated radiant (1.25+ ratio) provides a sleek, slimming effect, while a square radiant offers a bold, modern, and substantial presence.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>Four-prong, halo, bezel</td><td><strong>9/10. Structural Integrity.</strong> The radiant’s clipped corners are far more durable than the sharp points of a princess cut. It’s a "worry-free" shape that fits perfectly in almost any setting.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.00–1.05 (Sq) or 1.20–1.50 (El)</td><td><strong>10/10. The Choice is Yours.</strong> 1.25 to 1.35 is the "Golden Ratio" for most buyers, offering the perfect rectangular balance without looking too narrow or losing sparkle at the ends.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Radiant Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The radiant is for buyers who want a rectangular or square diamond with more sparkle than an emerald cut delivers — essentially an emerald cut with brilliant performance. It is the most practical "best of both worlds" shape in the catalog.

At 25–35% below round pricing with more clarity forgiveness than the emerald cut, it offers strong value for buyers who love the elongated look but don't want to pay VS1 clarity premiums.

