## **Asscher Cut Diamond: The Vintage Art Deco Icon**

**The Asscher cut is a square step-cut — the square equivalent of the emerald cut — featuring a distinctive octagonal outline, a deep pavilion, and the most dramatic hall-of-mirrors effect of any shape.**

![Asscher cut diamond infographic showing square step-cut geometry with X-pattern hall-of-mirrors effect and vintage Art Deco style on white background](http://diamondcritics.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/asscher-cut-diamond-art-deco-hall-of-mirrors-editorial-infographic-1024x683.jpg)

### **What Makes the Asscher Unique?**

The Asscher cut was created by the Royal Asscher Diamond Company of Amsterdam in 1902. Its defining features are its square outline with clipped (beveled) corners creating an octagonal shape, a notably high crown, a small table, and deeply cut step facets that create the most pronounced X-pattern hall-of-mirrors effect of any diamond shape.

The standard Asscher cut features 58 facets. The Royal Asscher Cut — a patented variation — features 74 facets and a different facet arrangement that produces an even more dramatic starburst pattern when viewed through the table.

The Asscher's vintage character is its primary appeal. It is the defining stone of the Art Deco era and remains the top choice for buyers drawn to 1920s and 1930s aesthetics, architectural jewelry, and geometric engagement ring styles.

#### **The Asscher's clarity challenge**

The Asscher has the same open-facet inclusion exposure as the emerald cut — arguably slightly worse, because the octagonal outline and deep pavilion concentrate light in the center of the stone, making central inclusions more visible than in rectangular emerald cuts.

VS1 is the absolute minimum for Asscher cuts, and VVS2 is strongly recommended for stones over 1.5ct. See the **[VVS2 diamond guide](https://diamondcritics.com/vvs2-diamond-clarity/)** for the full Asscher clarity analysis.

### **Asscher Diamond: The Data Profile**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Asscher Diamond Data</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Created</strong></td><td>1902, Royal Asscher Company</td><td><strong>10/10. The Pedigree.</strong> Joseph Asscher didn't just cut a diamond; he patented the world's first signature cut. It carries a level of historical "royalty" that modern hybrids simply can't touch.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Facet count</strong></td><td>58 (standard) or 74 (Royal Asscher)</td><td><strong>9/10. The Evolution.</strong> While the 58-facet original is a classic, the 74-facet Royal Asscher is a technical marvel that solves the "dark center" problem common in older step-cuts.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Optical style</strong></td><td>Dramatic X-pattern hall-of-mirrors</td><td><strong>10/10. Kaleidoscopic Magic.</strong> The Asscher creates a mesmerizing "X" pattern that draws the eye deep into the stone. It’s an architectural, hypnotic beauty that prioritizes depth over superficial sparkle.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Price vs. round</strong></td><td>30–40% less</td><td><strong>9/10. Elegant ROI.</strong> You are getting a world-class, designer silhouette for a fraction of the Round Brilliant price. It is the most cost-effective way to wear a "celebrity-tier" shape.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Clarity requirement</strong></td><td>VS1 mandatory; VVS2 recommended over 1.5ct</td><td><strong>2/10. The Honesty Tax.</strong> Like the Emerald cut, the Asscher is a "truth-teller." The large, open table will broadcast an SI1 inclusion like a billboard. You must pay the VS1 tax to keep this stone looking pristine.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Color sensitivity</strong></td><td>High — G or better</td><td><strong>6/10. The Prism Effect.</strong> Because of the step-cut geometry, Asschers act like prisms. They don't have the busy sparkle to hide body color, so stick to G or higher if you’re using a white metal setting.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Hall-of-mirrors</strong></td><td>Most dramatic of all shapes</td><td><strong>10/10. The Visual Signature.</strong> This is the "soul" of the Asscher. The concentric squares create a repetitive reflection that makes the diamond look like a bottomless pool of light.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Best setting</strong></td><td>Four-prong, bezel, Art Deco milgrain</td><td><strong>9/10. The Design Icon.</strong> Nothing suits an Asscher better than an Art Deco-inspired setting. A bezel mount emphasizes the clipped corners, making the stone look like a vintage masterpiece.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Ideal L/W ratio</strong></td><td>1.00–1.05 (Nearly Square)</td><td><strong>10/10. The Symmetrical Law.</strong> An Asscher that isn't square loses its identity. Perfect 1.00 symmetry is required to keep those "X" patterns aligned and the "hall of mirrors" balanced.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **Asscher Diamond: Who Should Buy It?**

The Asscher is for buyers who specifically love Art Deco aesthetics, vintage jewelry, and the distinctive X-pattern optical effect. It is the most niche of the mainstream shapes — buyers who choose an Asscher almost always do so because nothing else looks quite like it.

The combination of its vintage character, geometric beauty, and 30–40% price advantage over round makes it a compelling choice for the right buyer — but the clarity requirements must be taken seriously.

