## **The Complete Diamond Shapes Comparison Table (2026)**

**Every shape side-by-side for easy reference:**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Shape</th><th>Price vs. Round</th><th>Apparent Size</th><th>Best Clarity</th><th>Color Min</th><th>Farzana’s Ultimate Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Round</strong></td><td>Baseline</td><td>Standard</td><td>VS2–SI1</td><td>G-H</td><td><strong>10/10 for Light.</strong> The industry standard. You pay a 40% "Round Tax," but you get the best light performance and highest resale liquidity in the world.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Oval</strong></td><td>-20–30%</td><td>+10–15%</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td>G-H</td><td><strong>10/10 for Value.</strong> The current 2026 market leader. It makes fingers look thinner and looks significantly larger than a round for a fraction of the cost.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Cushion</strong></td><td>-20–30%</td><td>Compact</td><td>VS2–SI1</td><td>H or better</td><td><strong>9/10 for Romance.</strong> The best shape for halo settings. It holds color, so stick to yellow gold if you go below H-color. Incredible at hiding inclusions.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Emerald</strong></td><td>-30–40%</td><td>Elongated</td><td>VS1 min</td><td>G or better</td><td><strong>10/10 for Class.</strong> The "Quiet Luxury" choice. You save on price but MUST spend that savings on VS1+ clarity because it hides nothing.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Princess</strong></td><td>-20–30%</td><td>Square</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td>G-H</td><td><strong>8/10 for Modernity.</strong> High-energy sparkle in a crisp geometric frame. Beware of corner inclusions that can lead to structural chipping.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pear</strong></td><td>-25–35%</td><td>+10–15%</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td>G-H</td><td><strong>9/10 for Style.</strong> A sophisticated teardrop that maximizes size. Always protect the tip with a V-prong to avoid accidental chips.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Marquise</strong></td><td>-25–35%</td><td>+15–20%</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td>G-H</td><td><strong>10/10 for Size.</strong> The absolute winner for surface area. If you want a 1-carat diamond to look like a 1.5-carat, buy a Marquise.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Radiant</strong></td><td>-25–35%</td><td>Elongated</td><td>VS2–SI1</td><td>H or better</td><td><strong>10/10 for Practicality.</strong> Combines the Emerald silhouette with "Crushed Ice" sparkle. It is the best fancy shape for hiding SI1 inclusions.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asscher</strong></td><td>-30–40%</td><td>Compact</td><td>VS1 min</td><td>G or better</td><td><strong>7/10 for Niche.</strong> A vintage masterpiece for Art Deco lovers. Like the Emerald, it is a "transparency cut"—do not compromise on clarity.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Heart</strong></td><td>-15–25%</td><td>Standard</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td>G-H</td><td><strong>5/10 for Risk.</strong> The hardest cut to get right. Symmetry is everything here. Avoid hearts under 0.50ct as they lose their shape definition.</td></tr></tbody></table>

## **How Does Diamond Shape Affect Finger Appearance?**

**Elongated shapes (oval, marquise, pear) lengthen the appearance of the finger. Compact shapes (round, cushion, Asscher) sit more proportionally on the hand. Shape selection based on hand type is one of the most practical considerations in diamond buying.**

### **Shape Recommendations by Hand Type**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Hand Type</th><th>Best Shapes</th><th>Avoid</th><th>Farzana’s Stylist Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Short, Wide Fingers</strong></td><td>Marquise, Oval, Pear (North-South)</td><td>Round, Asscher, Cushion</td><td><strong>10/10 for Optics.</strong> Think of elongated stones as "high heels" for your hand. They force the eye to move vertically, instantly slimming the finger profile and creating a length illusion that round stones simply can't provide.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Long, Slender Fingers</strong></td><td>Any — especially Cushion, Round, Asscher</td><td>None</td><td><strong>9/10 for Versatility.</strong> You have the "Model Hands" of the diamond world. You are the only demographic that can carry compact, deep shapes like the Asscher or a chunky Cushion without the hand looking stubby. Enjoy the freedom.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Wide Knuckles</strong></td><td>Bezel-set Oval or Cushion</td><td>Sharp Corner Shapes (Princess)</td><td><strong>8/10 for Balance.</strong> The goal here is to draw the eye *away* from the joint. A bezel-set stone provides a smoother transition and more visual "weight," which balances the knuckle width better than a thin-pronged, sharp-angled stone.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Small Hands (Size 4–5)</strong></td><td>Oval, Pear (under 1.5ct), Cushion</td><td>Large Marquise</td><td><strong>7/10 for Proportion.</strong> Avoid "Diamond Overload." A massive marquise can look like a weapon on a size 4 finger. A 1.20ct Oval is your secret weapon—it delivers the visual impact of a 2ct stone without swallowing your hand whole.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Large Hands (Size 7+)</strong></td><td>Marquise, Elongated Oval, Radiant</td><td>Small Round (under 0.75ct)</td><td><strong>9/10 for Presence.</strong> You have the "real estate" to handle bold, elongated silhouettes. A small round diamond will get lost on your hand. Go for an elongated Radiant or Marquise to command the space you have.</td></tr></tbody></table>

Use the **[diamond size chart](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-size-chart/)** to understand how physical millimeter dimensions correspond to carat weights across different shapes — the physical diameter difference between shapes is often surprising.

## **Which Diamond Shape Hides Inclusions Best?**

**Brilliant cuts hide inclusions significantly better than step cuts. Within brilliant cuts, shapes with the most complex facet patterns (round, cushion modified, radiant) are most forgiving.**

This directly affects which clarity grade you need — and therefore the price you pay. See the complete clarity guides for each grade:

-   **[IF and FL clarity](https://diamondcritics.com/if-and-fl-diamond-clarity/)** — relevant for step-cut buyers who want absolute purity.  
    
-   **[VVS1 clarity](https://diamondcritics.com/vvs1-diamond-clarity/)** — the minimum recommendation for large Asscher/Emerald cuts.  
    
-   **[VVS2 clarity](https://diamondcritics.com/vvs2-diamond-clarity/)** — minimum for Emerald/Asscher over 1.5ct.  
    
-   **[VS1 clarity](https://diamondcritics.com/vs1-clarity-diamonds/)** — the sweet spot for all brilliant cuts and step-cuts under 1.25ct.  
    
-   **[VS2 clarity](https://diamondcritics.com/vs2-clarity-diamond/)** — excellent value for brilliant cuts under 1.5ct with audit.  
    

### **Inclusion Hiding Ability by Shape**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Shape</th><th>Inclusion Hiding Ability</th><th>Minimum Clarity</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Round Brilliant</strong></td><td>Excellent</td><td>VS2–SI1</td><td><strong>10/10. The Optical Shield.</strong> With 57 facets firing simultaneously, your eye is too busy processing light to notice a small crystal. This is the ultimate shape for "cheating" your way into an SI1.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Cushion Modified</strong></td><td>Excellent</td><td>VS2–SI1</td><td><strong>10/10. The Camouflage King.</strong> The "crushed-ice" pattern is essentially visual static. It breaks up inclusions so effectively that even a slightly "busy" SI1 can look completely eye-clean.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Oval</strong></td><td>Very Good</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td><strong>8/10. Brilliance with a Catch.</strong> The high brilliance masks flaws at the edges, but the center is more elongated and open. Stick to a high VS2 to ensure the "bow-tie" area stays clean.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Radiant</strong></td><td>Very Good</td><td>VS2–SI1</td><td><strong>9/10. The Hybrid Advantage.</strong> Like the cushion, its brilliant faceting creates enough "sparkle noise" to hide inclusions that would be glaringly obvious in an Emerald cut of the same shape.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pear</strong></td><td>Good</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td><strong>7/10. The Tip Risk.</strong> The rounded "belly" hides flaws well, but the narrow tip is far more transparent. An inclusion in the point is a 2/10 for aesthetics and a 10/10 for structural risk.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Marquise</strong></td><td>Good</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td><strong>7/10. Double Jeopardy.</strong> With two pointed ends, you have twice the chance of a visible inclusion sitting in a transparent "trap." Always audit the tips first.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Princess</strong></td><td>Good</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td><strong>7/10. Corner Scrutiny.</strong> The high brilliance in the center is great, but the corners are "truth-tellers." You need a VS2 to ensure those 90-degree points aren't harboring a structural crack.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Heart</strong></td><td>Good</td><td>VS1–VS2</td><td><strong>6/10. Transparency Pockets.</strong> The cleft (top dip) and the point are areas where light return can fail, leaving "windows" that expose inclusions. Audit the silhouette carefully.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Emerald</strong></td><td>Poor</td><td>VS1 mandatory</td><td><strong>1/10. The Truth-Teller.</strong> This isn't a diamond; it's a window. The long, open step facets provide zero "masking." If there is a speck of pepper in there, you will see it reflected ten times.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Asscher</strong></td><td>Poor</td><td>VS1 mandatory</td><td><strong>1/10. The X-Ray Cut.</strong> The concentric squares draw your eye right to the center. It’s an architectural masterpiece, but it demands VVS/VS1 purity or the "hall of mirrors" becomes a gallery of flaws.</td></tr></tbody></table>

## **Which Diamond Shape Is Best for Lab-Grown Diamonds?**

**All 10 shapes are available in lab-grown, and the shape value equation changes significantly — because the round brilliant's higher manufacturing cost is less pronounced in lab production.**

In natural diamonds, round brilliants command a 25–40% premium over fancy shapes because of rough yield loss. In lab-grown diamonds, the yield calculation is different — lab-grown rough is produced in controlled conditions where crystal orientation can be optimized for specific shapes. This reduces (but does not eliminate) the round premium in lab-grown diamonds.

The practical result: the price difference between a lab-grown round and a lab-grown oval is approximately 15–20% — smaller than the 25–30% gap in natural diamonds. Buyers who specifically want a round brilliant will find the premium more manageable in lab-grown than in natural.

For lab-grown buyers who want maximum size for budget: the oval and marquise remain the best value shapes — delivering more apparent surface area per dollar even in lab-grown pricing. As documented in the **[lab-grown vs natural diamond price guide](https://diamondcritics.com/lab-grown-vs-natural-diamond-price/)**, lab-grown prices across all shapes are 80–90% below natural equivalents in 2026.

## **Diamond Shape FAQs: Complete Masterclass**

